# Credentials and login — plain guide

Copy this file to **`CREDENTIALS.local.md`** in the repo root if you want a private copy;  
`CREDENTIALS.local.md` is listed in **`.gitignore`** so it is not committed.  
Do not put real production secrets in git.

---

## 1. Default passwords (copy-paste)

These are the **development defaults**. They work until you change them on the server or in env vars.

| What you pick on the login screen | Password to type |
|-------------------------------------|--------------------|
| **User** | `DevUser!1` |
| **Installer** | `DevInstall!1` |
| **Manufacturer** | `DevMfg!1` |

**Extra password (not a role on the screen):**  
If you choose **User** or **Installer** and type **`DevSupport!1`**, you still log in as User or Installer. The system treats it as a “support override” login. Manufacturer does **not** use this password.

---

## 2. Two different ways the PWA can check your password

### A) No gateway URL — “local dev” only

- Happens when **`VITE_GATEWAY_URL`** is **not** set (typical `npm run dev` in the PWA).
- The PWA checks passwords **in the browser** using the same default strings above.
- The header still shows **Change password** in dev: it opens a short explanation that passwords cannot be updated from the UI until you use a gateway (no secrets are stored from that dialog).
- You can change the default strings with Vite env vars (only for local builds):  
  `VITE_DEV_AUTH_USER`, `VITE_DEV_AUTH_INSTALLER`, `VITE_DEV_AUTH_MANUFACTURER`, `VITE_DEV_AUTH_SUPPORT`.

### B) Gateway URL set — real server login

- Happens when **`VITE_GATEWAY_URL`** points at your gateway (e.g. `http://127.0.0.1:8788`).
- The PWA sends the password to the **gateway**. The gateway compares it to **hashed** passwords in **`auth.json`** under that gateway’s **`CONFIG_DIR`**.
- The **first time** the gateway creates `auth.json`, it uses these environment variables (or the same defaults if unset):  
  `INITIAL_USER_PASSWORD`, `INITIAL_INSTALLER_PASSWORD`, `INITIAL_SUPPORT_PASSWORD`, `INITIAL_MANUFACTURER_PASSWORD`.
- If **`auth.json` already exists**, changing those env vars does **not** change existing passwords. You must use “change password” in the app or manufacturer “reset accounts” on the gateway.

---

## 3. Installer ID — what it is (not a password)

**Installer ID is not a password.** It is a **short label** for your company or team (a “fleet id”).

- When you choose **Installer** on the login screen, there is an extra box: **Installer ID (fleet)**.
- Whatever you type there is sent to the gateway and stored on your **session**.
- The gateway uses it so each installer only sees **their** sites in **`GET /api/sites`**. Site files under `sites/` can contain **`installer_id`** or **`installerId`**; that text must **match** what you typed at login, or that site will not appear in your list.
- **Nothing in the project picks this for you.** For testing, you can type anything consistent, for example: **`installer-demo`** every time, and use the same value inside test MQTT JSON if you fake discovery.

If you leave Installer ID **empty** on local dev (no gateway), login can still work; with the gateway, some installer-only actions need an installer id on the session.

---

## 4. Site ID (different from Installer ID)

When you log in through the **gateway**, the login request can include a **site id** (default in code is often **`site-001`** if you do not send one). That is which **site** you are working with for the session, not the installer company id.

---

## 5. Playwright E2E tests

Automated browser tests use the same default passwords: **`DevUser!1`**, **`DevInstall!1`**, **`DevMfg!1`**.

---

## 6. Quick “what do I type?” checklist

1. Open the PWA login page.  
2. Choose **User**, **Installer**, or **Manufacturer**.  
3. Password = see table in section 1.  
4. If **Installer**: optionally type an **Installer ID** you will reuse (e.g. `installer-demo`).  
5. If you use the **gateway**, ensure it is running and `VITE_GATEWAY_URL` matches its URL.

---

